<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<task id="011" project="code-quality-and-assurance-r2">
  <metadata>
    <title>Decompose AnalysisOrchestrationService into 3 Focused Services</title>
    <phase>2: Backend Structural Decomposition</phase>
    <status>completed</status>
    <estimated-hours>8</estimated-hours>
    <dependencies>001</dependencies>
    <blocks>013</blocks>
    <tags>refactoring, dotnet, bff-api, ai</tags>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Decompose AnalysisOrchestrationService.cs to reduce its constructor from 20 injected
    dependencies down to 10 or fewer by extracting 3 focused services: AnalysisDocumentLoader,
    AnalysisRagProcessor, and AnalysisResultPersistence. ExecutePlaybookAsync remains in the
    orchestrator but delegates its phases to the extracted services. Register all 3 new services
    in AnalysisServicesModule.cs.
  </prompt>

  <role>Senior .NET developer specializing in SOLID principles and service decomposition</role>

  <goal>
    AnalysisOrchestrationService.cs has a constructor with 10 or fewer parameters. Three new
    focused service files exist, each absorbing a cohesive set of dependencies. All existing
    functionality is preserved. dotnet build passes with zero errors.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      AnalysisOrchestrationService.cs orchestrates AI-powered document analysis. Its constructor
      currently accepts 20 dependencies, which is a strong signal that the class violates the
      Single Responsibility Principle and that constructor injection is being abused as a service
      locator. The 20-parameter constructor makes unit testing impractical, increases the
      likelihood of merge conflicts, and obscures the true responsibilities of the class.
      Phase 2 requires reducing the constructor to 10 or fewer parameters by extracting 3
      cohesive services: one for document loading and text extraction, one for RAG retrieval and
      caching, and one for persisting analysis outputs. ExecutePlaybookAsync is the core
      orchestration method and stays in the orchestrator; it simply calls the extracted services
      rather than calling dependencies directly.
    </background>
    <relevant-files>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/AnalysisOrchestrationService.cs (modify — primary target)</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/DI/AnalysisServicesModule.cs (modify — register new services)</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/AnalysisDocumentLoader.cs (create)</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/AnalysisRagProcessor.cs (create)</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/AnalysisResultPersistence.cs (create)</file>
    </relevant-files>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="ADR-009">
      Redis is the only caching layer. IDistributedCache must remain the abstraction used for
      RAG result caching inside AnalysisRagProcessor. Do not introduce an in-memory fallback or
      hybrid cache unless profiling proves a need.
    </constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-010">
      Register new services as concrete types in AnalysisServicesModule.cs. Constructor parameter
      count for AnalysisOrchestrationService must be 10 or fewer after refactoring. Total
      non-framework DI registrations across the solution must remain at or below 15.
    </constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-009.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-010.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">
      Read AnalysisOrchestrationService.cs in full. For each constructor parameter, list which
      methods use it. Group methods by the dependency cluster they belong to:
      (a) document loading / text extraction, (b) RAG search and caching, (c) output persistence
      and indexing. Record this mapping before writing any new files.
    </step>
    <step order="2">
      Create AnalysisDocumentLoader.cs in src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/.
      Move into it: ExtractDocumentTextAsync, ReloadAnalysisFromDataverseAsync,
      GetOrReloadFromDataverseAsync.
      Constructor dependencies to absorb: IDataverseService, ISpeFileOperations, ITextExtractor,
      IDistributedCache (document cache only), IHttpContextAccessor,
      ILogger&lt;AnalysisDocumentLoader&gt;.
    </step>
    <step order="3">
      Create AnalysisRagProcessor.cs in src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/.
      Move into it: ProcessRagKnowledgeAsync, GetOrSearchRagCacheAsync, ComputeRagCacheKey,
      GetTenantIdFromClaims.
      Constructor dependencies to absorb: IRagService, RagQueryBuilder, IDistributedCache (RAG
      cache), CacheMetrics, ILogger&lt;AnalysisRagProcessor&gt;.
    </step>
    <step order="4">
      Create AnalysisResultPersistence.cs in src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/.
      Move into it: StoreDocumentProfileOutputsAsync, EnqueueRagIndexingJobAsync, and any
      working-document finalization logic.
      Constructor dependencies to absorb: IDataverseService (output writes), IWorkingDocumentService,
      IStorageRetryPolicy, JobSubmissionService, ILogger&lt;AnalysisResultPersistence&gt;.
    </step>
    <step order="5">
      Update AnalysisOrchestrationService constructor. Replace all absorbed raw dependencies with
      the 3 injected service instances plus only the dependencies that genuinely belong in the
      orchestrator (e.g., the AI tool runner, playbook loader, metrics). Verify the count is 10
      or fewer.
    </step>
    <step order="6">
      Refactor ExecutePlaybookAsync to delegate document loading, RAG processing, and result
      persistence phases to the 3 injected services. The orchestrator method should read as a
      clear sequence of high-level steps with no implementation details inline.
    </step>
    <step order="7">
      Refactor ExecuteAnalysisAsync in the same manner — delegate phases rather than calling
      low-level dependencies directly.
    </step>
    <step order="8">
      Register AnalysisDocumentLoader, AnalysisRagProcessor, and AnalysisResultPersistence in
      AnalysisServicesModule.cs as concrete scoped registrations following ADR-010.
    </step>
    <step order="9">
      Run dotnet build from the repository root. Fix all compilation errors before proceeding.
      Do not proceed to step 10 until the build is green.
    </step>
    <step order="10">
      Count the parameters in the AnalysisOrchestrationService constructor. If the count exceeds
      10, identify which remaining dependencies can be absorbed into one of the 3 extracted
      services or a new one, and extract accordingly.
    </step>
    <step order="11">
      Update projects/code-quality-and-assurance-r2/tasks/TASK-INDEX.md — mark task 011 complete.
    </step>
  </steps>

  <outputs>
    <output type="file">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/AnalysisDocumentLoader.cs</output>
    <output type="file">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/AnalysisRagProcessor.cs</output>
    <output type="file">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/AnalysisResultPersistence.cs</output>
    <output type="file">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/AnalysisOrchestrationService.cs (modified)</output>
    <output type="file">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/DI/AnalysisServicesModule.cs (modified)</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>AnalysisOrchestrationService constructor has 10 or fewer parameters</criterion>
    <criterion>Three new focused service files created: AnalysisDocumentLoader.cs, AnalysisRagProcessor.cs, AnalysisResultPersistence.cs</criterion>
    <criterion>All existing functionality of ExecutePlaybookAsync and ExecuteAnalysisAsync is preserved — no behavior changes</criterion>
    <criterion>All 3 new services are registered in AnalysisServicesModule.cs</criterion>
    <criterion>dotnet build passes with zero errors across the entire solution</criterion>
    <criterion>IDistributedCache usage for RAG caching remains inside AnalysisRagProcessor only (ADR-009 compliance)</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
